WEBVTT

00:00:00.250 --> 00:00:01.890
<v Instructor>Okay, so another question that has come up</v>

00:00:01.890 --> 00:00:04.930
in the exam is around the root user privileges.

00:00:04.930 --> 00:00:06.640
So the root user is the account owner.

00:00:06.640 --> 00:00:09.210
It's the first user that is going to be used

00:00:09.210 --> 00:00:12.280
when the account is created and the root user

00:00:12.280 --> 00:00:16.920
has complete access to all AWS services and resources.

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:19.810
And the idea is that the root user can do some actions

00:00:19.810 --> 00:00:22.210
that even the most privileged created user

00:00:22.210 --> 00:00:23.680
in your account cannot do.

00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:26.150
And so, this is what we have to look at in this lecture.

00:00:26.150 --> 00:00:28.160
So, by the way, if you're using the root user,

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:29.820
please lock away the account

00:00:29.820 --> 00:00:31.150
'cause you shouldn't be using it

00:00:31.150 --> 00:00:32.600
and as well as your excess keys,

00:00:32.600 --> 00:00:34.340
secret access keys, this kind of stuff.

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:36.480
So do not use the root account for everyday tasks,

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:37.600
even administrative tasks.

00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:41.380
For this, create a specific admin user in your accounts,

00:00:41.380 --> 00:00:43.450
but some actions can only be performed

00:00:43.450 --> 00:00:45.430
by the root user and you have to remember them,

00:00:45.430 --> 00:00:47.420
especially the one that I put in bold.

00:00:47.420 --> 00:00:49.170
So, the first one is that only the root user

00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:50.880
can change the account settings,

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:53.150
such as the account name, the email address,

00:00:53.150 --> 00:00:56.470
the root user password and root user access keys,

00:00:56.470 --> 00:00:59.310
view certain tax invoices, close your account,

00:00:59.310 --> 00:01:00.640
so it can only be done by the root user

00:01:00.640 --> 00:01:02.680
and that's pretty helpful, I would say,

00:01:02.680 --> 00:01:04.710
restore IAM user permissions,

00:01:04.710 --> 00:01:08.940
change or cancel your AWS Support plan,

00:01:08.940 --> 00:01:11.977
register as a seller in the Reserved Instance Marketplace.

00:01:11.977 --> 00:01:13.080
And this one is important,

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:14.710
so I'll give you a use case for this.

00:01:14.710 --> 00:01:16.460
For example, say you are buying

00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:18.770
a Reserved Instance for three years,

00:01:18.770 --> 00:01:20.010
but after two years, you realize

00:01:20.010 --> 00:01:22.590
you don't need to have it anymore,

00:01:22.590 --> 00:01:25.220
so what you can do is that there is a marketplace

00:01:25.220 --> 00:01:28.110
in which you can sell back your Reserved Instance

00:01:28.110 --> 00:01:30.740
and so to do so, you need to register as a seller first

00:01:30.740 --> 00:01:33.460
and only the root user can do it.

00:01:33.460 --> 00:01:36.550
Finally, two more things or three more things,

00:01:36.550 --> 00:01:39.400
to configure an Amazon S3 bucket to enable MFA,

00:01:39.400 --> 00:01:41.980
to edit or delete an S3 bucket policy

00:01:41.980 --> 00:01:44.530
that is getting an invalid VPC ID

00:01:44.530 --> 00:01:49.130
or VPC endpoint ID, to sign up for GovCloud as well.

00:01:49.130 --> 00:01:51.040
So you do have to remember those,

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:53.030
especially the one that I put in bold

00:01:53.030 --> 00:01:56.560
because the exam may ask you which types of actions

00:01:56.560 --> 00:01:59.390
are only possible to be done by the root user

00:01:59.390 --> 00:02:00.440
and you have to know.

00:02:00.440 --> 00:02:01.273
Okay, that's it.

00:02:01.273 --> 00:02:03.843
I hope you liked it and I will see you in the next lecture.